URL: https://www.reddit.com/r/ValueInvesting/comments/1o39e0q/days_like_today_are_a_reminder_that_amzn_is_not/
Subreddit: r/ValueInvesting
Title: Days like today are a reminder that AMZN is not on the same level as MSFT, NVDA, GOOG, AAPL, and META
Author: u/SouthIsland48
Score: 0 | Comments: 37 | Upvote Ratio: 44.0%
Created: 2025-10-11 02:46:38
Content: I always see AMZN touted as a no brainer MAG 7 stock, but days like today are a friendly reminder that they are not in fact a pure software/high margin tech play as it goes without saying their large expensive retail enterprise is a massive part of the company you're buying.

For better or for worse.

That isn't to say AMZN is a bad company to own, but rather their business model is so vastly different than the others.

And look I get AWS is a gem of a business, but as long as AWS is tied to the hip with a bloated retail enterprise, I will continue to invest elsewhere for cloud technology. I would not be shocked at all if AWS splits from AMZN if the company continues to tread water valuation wise for the next few years.
================================================================================
